Actually the work goes rather quickly as the parts, although extremely
advanced, are also built to be user friendly. Slipping a circuit board
here, sliding out one from there, replacing a processor or two and a
bit of quick soldering has the board that NIGHTSHIFT is working on in
good shape.

In fact as NIGHTSHIFT is sliding his last piece into place PROWL is
doing much the same thing.

&quot;Okay!&quot; PROWL said as he spoke into his radio. &quot;Give us some power.&quot;

It took a moment and then there was a thrumming of power through the
communication boards. There was a single spark then then the lights
flickered and went green, it was working again.

PROWL stepped over and activated a switch and the boards began to
light up as the back up antenna went into operation.

&quot;Have we got it?&quot; POLAR CLAW said as he came from the lower levels.

The lights on the boards registered a signal being sent from the tower
to the satellite up in space, it registered the satellites computers,
there was an acknowledgement, a request for data . . . .

               . . . &quot;Uh oh&quot; WOLFGANG said as he saw the response. . . .

                       . . . . there was no returning other response
from the satellite uplink , no data returned.

&quot;Could it be the satellite?&quot; WOLFGANG said with a shrug.

